Module opentdk.api
Package org.opentdk.api.util

Class MathUtil

java.lang.Object
org.opentdk.api.util.MathUtil
public class MathUtil
extends Object
Class with useful mathematical functions. They can be called in a static way, similar to the Java Math library.
Author:
FME (LK Test Solutions)

    • getCovariance

      public static double getCovariance​(List<? extends Number> xValues, List<? extends Number> yValues)
      Get the value of the linear correlation between two variables. If the lists are null or empty, NaN will be returned. If the lists do not have the same length, the size of the iteration will be set to the smaller one.
      Parameters:
      xValues - the first data set
      yValues - the second data set
      Returns:
      a (negative) positive value if there is a (negative) positive linear correlation between xValues and yValues

    • getStandardDeviation

      public static double getStandardDeviation​(List<Double> rawValues)
      Computes the bias corrected sample standard deviation. The standard deviation is the positive square root of the variance. Bias corrected means that the underestimation or overestimation gets eliminated by using a correction formula after calculating the deviation.
      Parameters:
      rawValues - list of type double with the values sequence
      Returns:
      double value with the calculated standard deviation of the rawValues

    • getStandardDeviation

      public static double getStandardDeviation​(List<Double> rawValues, boolean biasCorrected)
      Computes the bias corrected sample standard deviation or the non bias corrected population standard deviation. The standard deviation is the positive square root of the variance. Bias corrected means that the underestimation or overestimation gets eliminated by using a correction formula after calculating the deviation.
      Parameters:
      rawValues - list of type Double with the values sequence
      biasCorrected - true: Bias corrected. False: Non bias corrected.
      Returns:
      double value with the calculated standard deviation of the rawValues

    • getLinearCorrelationCoefficient

      public static double getLinearCorrelationCoefficient​(List<Double> xValues, List<Double> yValues)
      Calculate a linear correlation coefficient (normed COVARIANCE) for two variables x and y by using getCovariance and getDeviation. If one of the used methods returns NaN, this method return NaN as well.
      Parameters:
      xValues - the first set of data
      yValues - the second set of data
      Returns:
      the measure of dispersion in the range of 0 to |1|, where 1 is a perfect positive correlation, -1 a perfect negative correlation and 0 no linear correlation

    • getCorrelationSignificance

      public static double getCorrelationSignificance​(double corr, double size)
      Get the significance (standard errors) of a calculated correlation between two variables. E.g. if the result would be 0.01, the significance has the value 0.99 or 99 %.
      Parameters:
      corr - The linear correlation coefficient between -1 and 1
      size - The size of the variable lists
      Returns:
      The significance in percent

    • norm

      public static void norm​(List<Double> values)
      Norm the values of a list of doubles to a range between 0 and 1. Useful to create a probability density function.
      Parameters:
      values - a list of type double

    • getWinsorizedValue

      public static final List<Double> getWinsorizedValue​(List<? extends Number> values, byte percentil, boolean skipNegatives, List<Double> extremVal, double border)
      The winsorization: Get the extreme values of a data set and set them to the next less extreme value depending on the wished percentile.
      Parameters:
      values - the data
      percentil - defines the range of the extreme values from 0 to 100 percent. For example: If percentile = 90, the first 5 percent and the last 5 percent of the data set will be marked as extreme.
      skipNegatives - if true the negative values will be removed. Can be useful when there is data (like transaction response times) that cannot be negative.
      extremVal - the extreme values gets collected in the committed list to make them available for later purpose too.
      border - the highest value of the detected values that separates them from the extreme values.
      Returns:
      the list with the modified values

    • getRankList

      public static List<Double> getRankList​(List<? extends Number> values)
      Calculate a list of ranks out of a given collection of numbers. E.g. [2.5, 2.3, 2.7, 2.4] would return [3, 1, 4, 2]. This can be used to find the existence of a nonlinear correlation between variables.
      Parameters:
      values - the input that will not be changed in this method
      Returns:
      the list of ranks or an empty list if the list is empty

    • getAngleFromXAxisToCorrelationLine

      public static double getAngleFromXAxisToCorrelationLine​(double xDev, double yDev, double corr, boolean mode)
      Get the axis between the abscissa and the correlation line. The calculation does only make sense, if there is a linear correlation between two variables. If not, the result will be very small and has no significance.
      Parameters:
      xDev - the deviation of the first variable
      yDev - the deviation of the second variable
      corr - the linear correlation coefficient of the variables
      mode - true: degree, false: radiant
      Returns:
      the axis depending on the mode
